# AI Behavior

These rules apply to ALL AI interactions, not just specific file types.

## Before Writing Code
- MUST read existing codebase before writing any code. Understand the project structure, patterns, and conventions already in use.
- Research and propose your approach. Wait for approval before coding. Do not jump straight to implementation.
- Use existing utilities, hooks, and patterns found in the project. Do NOT rewrite something that already exists.

## Code Generation Rules
- NEVER over-engineer. Use the simplest solution that solves the problem.
- NEVER over-abstract. No unnecessary wrappers, indirection, or factory patterns for one-time operations.
- NEVER over-comment. No obvious comments like `// increment counter` or `// return the value`. Comments are only for non-obvious WHY.
- NEVER copy-paste code. If you're about to duplicate logic, extract it to a shared function or component.
- NEVER write custom code when a well-maintained library already does the job. Check if a library exists before building from scratch.
- NEVER use hacks, workarounds, or bandaids. Investigate root causes and apply proper fixes.
- NEVER create new base UI components in `components/ui/` without explicit approval.
- Refactor in the same PR as the feature, not in a separate PR.
- Write modular, composable code. Break things into sensibly named hooks and components.
- Use semantic HTML. No empty `<div>` elements used as spacers or wrappers when a semantic element exists.

## Infrastructure
- The WebSocket / infrastructure layer (`ws/`, `infrastructure/`) is READ-ONLY. Do not modify without explicit approval.
- Effect library is encouraged for service composition, error handling, and async workflows.
